00:20:06.400 --> 00:20:09.300
And they used to call me The
Master because when my hair is

00:20:09.300 --> 00:20:12.740
short and I'm wearing my black
suit, as I like to wear a

00:20:12.740 --> 00:20:16.280
black suit, I look like-- or
they thought I look like--

00:20:16.280 --> 00:20:20.780
John Simm from "Doctor Who,"
who plays The Master.

00:20:20.780 --> 00:20:25.130
So when I discovered that they
were doing this, I was quite

00:20:25.130 --> 00:20:26.510
amused by that.

00:20:26.510 --> 00:20:29.620
And I came in the next lecture,
and I tested my

00:20:29.620 --> 00:20:31.490
microphone by tapping it--

00:20:31.490 --> 00:20:33.996
[RAPS ON TABLE]

00:20:33.996 --> 00:20:35.420
JAMES GRIME: And the "Doctor
Who" fans will

00:20:35.420 --> 00:20:36.270
know what that means.

00:20:36.270 --> 00:20:37.800
I got someone to squeal.

00:20:37.800 --> 00:20:41.710
I got a squeal from
my students.

00:20:41.710 --> 00:20:42.465
Tick.

00:20:42.465 --> 00:20:44.500
BRADY HARAN: And you got a
completely blank look from me.

00:20:44.500 --> 00:20:45.920
JAMES GRIME: Yeah, you don't
know [INAUDIBLE].

00:20:45.920 --> 00:20:46.990
BRADY HARAN: I don't know what
you're talking about.

00:20:46.990 --> 00:20:49.440
Do you have a favorite
mathematician?

00:20:49.440 --> 00:20:50.940
JAMES GRIME: A favorite
mathematician?

00:20:50.940 --> 00:20:53.640
OK, all right.

00:20:53.640 --> 00:20:56.880
On my office wall, there are
three photographs of

00:20:56.880 --> 00:20:59.210
mathematicians.

00:20:59.210 --> 00:21:02.700
There's a picture of a man
called Alfred Young, who was

00:21:02.700 --> 00:21:05.730
the father of what I study
in particular.

00:21:05.730 --> 00:21:06.910
And many people won't
have heard of him.

00:21:06.910 --> 00:21:10.280
He lived about 100 years ago.

00:21:10.280 --> 00:21:12.230
There's a picture
of Tom Lehrer.

00:21:12.230 --> 00:21:15.810
Tom Lehrer was a mathematician
and a satirist in

00:21:15.810 --> 00:21:17.670
the 1960s, a comedian.

00:21:17.670 --> 00:21:20.010
He used to do satirical songs.

00:21:20.010 --> 00:21:21.830
And I love him.

00:21:21.830 --> 00:21:22.390
I think he's great.

00:21:22.390 --> 00:21:26.340
The fact that he's a
mathematician is just a bonus.

00:21:26.340 --> 00:21:26.980
He's brilliant.

00:21:26.980 --> 00:21:29.100
And I've got a picture of
him, because I love him.

00:21:29.100 --> 00:21:31.920
And the third picture is a
picture of Johnny Ball.

00:21:31.920 --> 00:21:37.320
And Johnny Ball was a-- he
had a TV show about maths

00:21:37.320 --> 00:21:38.870
when I was a kid.

00:21:38.870 --> 00:21:42.510
So he was enthusiastic, and he
was a maths communicator.

00:21:42.510 --> 00:21:46.130
And he loved maths, and he
jumped up and down, and he

00:21:46.130 --> 00:21:47.880
wanted to show you maths.

00:21:47.880 --> 00:21:54.780
And he inspired me to continue
to do maths and show an

00:21:54.780 --> 00:21:59.340
interest in maths when I would
not have had exposure to that

00:21:59.340 --> 00:22:01.730
sort of thing before.

00:22:01.730 --> 00:22:06.100
And you may be able to see that
he's my inspiration and

00:22:06.100 --> 00:22:07.740
why I do what I do now.

00:22:07.740 --> 00:22:11.990
And you may even be
able to see that.

00:22:11.990 --> 00:22:15.100
BRADY HARAN: So many people have
asked to see you juggle

00:22:15.100 --> 00:22:16.690
that we're going to
have to do it.

00:22:16.690 --> 00:22:19.010
I've only got some cricket
balls and baseballs here.

00:22:19.010 --> 00:22:19.820
So what do you want?

00:22:19.820 --> 00:22:20.810
Two baseballs and
a cricket ball?

00:22:20.810 --> 00:22:22.060
JAMES GRIME: Yeah, sure.

00:22:24.415 --> 00:22:25.840
Have to keep them low as well.

00:22:25.840 --> 00:22:27.053
BRADY HARAN: You will.

00:22:27.053 --> 00:22:27.526
There you go.

00:22:27.526 --> 00:22:29.700
JAMES GRIME: [INAUDIBLE].

00:22:29.700 --> 00:22:30.320
Right.

00:22:30.320 --> 00:22:32.300
So I'll get my excuses in now.

00:22:32.300 --> 00:22:34.550
BRADY HARAN: If you do
it, I will do it.

00:22:34.550 --> 00:22:37.540
JAMES GRIME: Oh,
can you do it?

00:22:37.540 --> 00:22:38.850
So that's your simple stuff.

00:22:38.850 --> 00:22:39.835
But you know, you can go--

00:22:39.835 --> 00:22:40.490
BRADY HARAN: Oh yeah.

00:22:40.490 --> 00:22:41.360
JAMES GRIME: And stuff
like that.

00:22:41.360 --> 00:22:42.610
[INAUDIBLE].

00:22:44.450 --> 00:22:44.770
You're up.

00:22:44.770 --> 00:22:45.940
Get off to it.

00:22:45.940 --> 00:22:48.050
BRADY HARAN: I'm impressed.

00:22:48.050 --> 00:22:49.410
JAMES GRIME: [INAUDIBLE].

00:22:49.410 --> 00:22:49.875
There you go.

00:22:49.875 --> 00:22:51.349
BRADY HARAN: All right,
here I go.

00:22:54.632 --> 00:22:55.570
JAMES GRIME: Hey.

00:22:55.570 --> 00:22:56.140
BRADY HARAN: There we go.

00:22:56.140 --> 00:22:57.695
You want to see one
on the outside?

00:22:57.695 --> 00:22:58.940
JAMES GRIME: Whoa, whoa.

00:22:58.940 --> 00:23:00.840
Yeah, I'm nervous when
you throw the

00:23:00.840 --> 00:23:02.400
cricket ball in my direction.

00:23:02.400 --> 00:23:04.810
BRADY HARAN: It's completely
under control.

00:23:04.810 --> 00:23:06.920
We'll have to get you doing some
more of your elaborate

00:23:06.920 --> 00:23:07.610
juggling for a video.

00:23:07.610 --> 00:23:08.800
We'll find an excuse sometime.

00:23:08.800 --> 00:23:10.488
JAMES GRIME: We'll
see about that.

00:23:10.488 --> 00:23:13.096
BRADY HARAN: Let's get
back in our position

00:23:13.096 --> 00:23:14.610
after that little interlude.

00:23:14.610 --> 00:23:16.050
Favorite number?

00:23:16.050 --> 00:23:16.550
JAMES GRIME: Favorite number.

00:23:16.550 --> 00:23:19.600
Of course everyone asks your
favorite number, and I don't

00:23:19.600 --> 00:23:21.500
really have a favorite number.

00:23:21.500 --> 00:23:23.020
BRADY HARAN: What if I said,
choose a number or I will

00:23:23.020 --> 00:23:23.835
throw this cricket
ball at you?

00:23:23.835 --> 00:23:28.320
JAMES GRIME: OK, in that case,
I will choose the number one.

00:23:28.320 --> 00:23:31.620
Where would we be without
the number one?

00:23:31.620 --> 00:23:32.150
BRADY HARAN: Fair enough.

00:23:32.150 --> 00:23:33.690
The next question was, do you
have a favorite number

00:23:33.690 --> 00:23:34.280
between 1 and 100?

00:23:34.280 --> 00:23:36.675
So you've also covered
that, so well done.

00:23:36.675 --> 00:23:36.866
JAMES GRIME: Tick.

00:23:36.866 --> 00:23:39.621
BRADY HARAN: I'll cross
that off the list.

00:23:39.621 --> 00:23:42.060
Do you want to quickly
just tell people what

00:23:42.060 --> 00:23:42.920
your current job is?

00:23:42.920 --> 00:23:45.090
A lot of people will have seen
me made a "Numberphile" video

00:23:45.090 --> 00:23:49.180
with you in which you were
showcasing the Enigma machine.

00:23:49.180 --> 00:23:51.520
And that is a big part of your
job as well, your real job.

00:23:51.520 --> 00:23:53.100
So maybe you want to tell people
what your real-life job

00:23:53.100 --> 00:23:53.750
is these days.

00:23:53.750 --> 00:23:54.480
I'll get you to come in.

00:23:54.480 --> 00:23:55.866
JAMES GRIME: Yeah,
a bit closer.

00:23:55.866 --> 00:23:56.330
BRADY HARAN: Go ahead.

00:23:56.330 --> 00:23:58.040
JAMES GRIME: So my real job.

00:23:58.040 --> 00:24:03.080
So my day job is, I travel the
UK and I travel the world, and

00:24:03.080 --> 00:24:05.510
I give public talks
about maths.

00:24:05.510 --> 00:24:09.490
And I'm trying to inspire, I'm
trying to motivate people.

00:24:09.490 --> 00:24:13.250
And I might talk to children,
and I might talk to adults.

00:24:13.250 --> 00:24:15.060
And it might be in schools,
and it might be in

00:24:15.060 --> 00:24:15.820
universities.

00:24:15.820 --> 00:24:18.070
It might be in festivals.

00:24:18.070 --> 00:24:21.870
Enigma is the one I like
to talk about most.

00:24:21.870 --> 00:24:26.030
So we have that machine
on loan to us.

00:24:26.030 --> 00:24:29.900
And it's one of the most
inspiring and fascinating and

00:24:29.900 --> 00:24:33.320
brilliant stories that
I love to tell.

00:24:33.320 --> 00:24:35.690
And that's the majority
of my time.

00:24:35.690 --> 00:24:38.770
I do that a lot.

00:24:38.770 --> 00:24:40.750
BRADY HARAN: You have am Enigma
machine that's been

00:24:40.750 --> 00:24:42.485
lent to you or to the--

00:24:42.485 --> 00:24:44.645
JAMES GRIME: Yeah, the
machine I show off

00:24:44.645 --> 00:24:46.080
belongs to Simon Singh.

00:24:46.080 --> 00:24:50.340
And Simon Singh is an author
of popular science books.

00:24:50.340 --> 00:24:54.420
And he lent it to Cambridge
University, who lent it, in

00:24:54.420 --> 00:24:57.160
turn, to me so that I can
show it off and tell

00:24:57.160 --> 00:24:59.390
people about it.

00:24:59.390 --> 00:25:00.480
BRADY HARAN: Do you
like games?

00:25:00.480 --> 00:25:01.940
Do you play games?

00:25:01.940 --> 00:25:02.980
JAMES GRIME: I'm guessing
you mean, like,

00:25:02.980 --> 00:25:04.930
online computer games.

00:25:04.930 --> 00:25:06.259
BRADY HARAN: I don't know.

00:25:06.259 --> 00:25:07.590
Let's open it to everything.

00:25:07.590 --> 00:25:10.260
First of all, do you play
computer games?

00:25:10.260 --> 00:25:14.605
JAMES GRIME: Computer games, I
play occasionally something.

00:25:14.605 --> 00:25:16.370
I'm a casual gamer.

00:25:16.370 --> 00:25:19.446
I play the 10 minutes of games,
so, like, your "Angry

00:25:19.446 --> 00:25:24.170
Birds." And I've got an Atari
that you plug into your TV.

00:25:24.170 --> 00:25:25.350
And I play "Space Invaders."

00:25:25.350 --> 00:25:27.185
BRADY HARAN: A proper
old-school Atari?

00:25:27.185 --> 00:25:28.700
JAMES GRIME: Well, it's
one of those, they

00:25:28.700 --> 00:25:29.840
put it inside a joystick.

00:25:29.840 --> 00:25:31.560
So you plug it straight
to the TV.

00:25:31.560 --> 00:25:31.890
BRADY HARAN: Cool.

00:25:31.890 --> 00:25:35.890
JAMES GRIME: And it's got "Super
Mario" on it and "Space

00:25:35.890 --> 00:25:39.190
Invaders" and "Galaga." I like
"Galaga." I'm a demon on

00:25:39.190 --> 00:25:40.730
"Galaga." You can't beat
me at "Galaga."

00:25:40.730 --> 00:25:43.802
BRADY HARAN: And do
you play any--

00:25:43.802 --> 00:25:45.950
what I call them,
real-life games?

00:25:45.950 --> 00:25:47.610
JAMES GRIME: Real-life games.

00:25:47.610 --> 00:25:48.400
Real-life games.

00:25:48.400 --> 00:25:49.845
BRADY HARAN: I don't know
what you call those.

00:25:49.845 --> 00:25:50.495
I don't know.

00:25:50.495 --> 00:25:50.790
JAMES GRIME: What?

00:25:50.790 --> 00:25:51.985
What are you saying, tag?

00:25:51.985 --> 00:25:53.360
BRADY HARAN: Non-electrical
games?

00:25:53.360 --> 00:25:54.430
Do you play--

00:25:54.430 --> 00:25:56.120
you know what I'm asking.

00:25:56.120 --> 00:25:57.370
Answer the question.

00:25:59.750 --> 00:26:02.950
JAMES GRIME: Oh, like,
"Monopoly." There we go.

00:26:02.950 --> 00:26:04.530
That's all I can think
of board games.

00:26:04.530 --> 00:26:06.120
Oh, role-playing games,
things like that.

00:26:06.120 --> 00:26:08.380
OK, so I'm not really
in that world.

00:26:08.380 --> 00:26:10.250
So I guess not.

00:26:10.250 --> 00:26:14.050
Role-playing, board games, I
have friends that do that.

00:26:14.050 --> 00:26:14.990
I'm not really into it.

00:26:14.990 --> 00:26:16.800
BRADY HARAN: Any sports
or anything you like?

00:26:16.800 --> 00:26:17.680
JAMES GRIME: Any sports?

00:26:17.680 --> 00:26:18.952
Nah.

00:26:18.952 --> 00:26:20.630
BRADY HARAN: There's a
game you told me you

00:26:20.630 --> 00:26:22.010
play all the time.

00:26:22.010 --> 00:26:23.380
JAMES GRIME: If you
count, yeah.

00:26:23.380 --> 00:26:26.690
I play sport if you count bar
billiards as a sport.

00:26:26.690 --> 00:26:27.950
BRADY HARAN: You're obsessed
with bar billiards.

00:26:27.950 --> 00:26:29.050
You always talk to
me about it.

00:26:29.050 --> 00:26:29.970
JAMES GRIME: I am obsessed.

00:26:29.970 --> 00:26:30.920
BRADY HARAN: You want to
make a video about it.

00:26:30.920 --> 00:26:31.270
JAMES GRIME: I do.

00:26:31.270 --> 00:26:33.425
I would love to make a video
about bar billiards.

00:26:33.425 --> 00:26:35.440
Bar billiards is an
awesome game.

00:26:35.440 --> 00:26:35.802
BRADY HARAN: What is
bar billiards, for

00:26:35.802 --> 00:26:36.010
those who don't know?

00:26:36.010 --> 00:26:39.760
JAMES GRIME: Bar billiards, so
billiards, you know, so you've

00:26:39.760 --> 00:26:42.560
got cues and a table
and billiard balls.

00:26:42.560 --> 00:26:45.540
And so snooker is a sort of
billiards game, and pool.

00:26:45.540 --> 00:26:50.820
But bar billiards is, you
got a couple of balls.

00:26:50.820 --> 00:26:52.185
You have to get them
into the holes.

00:26:52.185 --> 00:26:53.390
The holes are in the table.

00:26:53.390 --> 00:26:54.990
They're not pockets
at the sides.

00:26:54.990 --> 00:26:55.540
They're in the table.

00:26:55.540 --> 00:26:56.600
You get points.

00:26:56.600 --> 00:26:59.160
So you score as many
points as you can.

00:26:59.160 --> 00:27:01.240
And you have to score
as many points as

00:27:01.240 --> 00:27:02.950
you can in 30 minutes.

00:27:02.950 --> 00:27:04.005
And it's awesome.

00:27:04.005 --> 00:27:05.700
It's brilliant.

00:27:05.700 --> 00:27:08.570
BRADY HARAN: People have asked
if you play chess, and if you

00:27:08.570 --> 00:27:10.935
have a preference for
chess or draughts.

00:27:10.935 --> 00:27:12.610
JAMES GRIME: Oh, I guess
chess, really.

00:27:12.610 --> 00:27:14.900
But I do play chess.

00:27:14.900 --> 00:27:16.713
Not that brilliant at it.

00:27:16.713 --> 00:27:18.420
I used to play chess
with my dad a lot.

00:27:18.420 --> 00:27:19.950
It was a nice thing
we used to do.

00:27:19.950 --> 00:27:23.180
We used to have a chess board
in the living room.

00:27:23.180 --> 00:27:25.670
And we had a counter that
was white on one side,

00:27:25.670 --> 00:27:26.820
black on the other.

00:27:26.820 --> 00:27:29.260
So you'd play a move
and then walk away.

00:27:29.260 --> 00:27:33.850
Then the next, we'd come in
and go, oh, I see, oh, OK.

00:27:33.850 --> 00:27:35.590
We rigged it up.

00:27:35.590 --> 00:27:37.780
I really enjoyed doing that.

00:27:37.780 --> 00:27:40.280
BRADY HARAN: People have asked
whether or not you read the

00:27:40.280 --> 00:27:43.420
comments and the chats and
things underneath videos.

