I'm sorry.

00:28:00.300 --> 00:28:04.795
And then on the "Numberphile"
ones, I check, yes.

00:28:04.795 --> 00:28:07.060
So yes.

00:28:07.060 --> 00:28:09.390
I was considering denying
it, because it kind of

00:28:09.390 --> 00:28:10.290
makes me less cool.

00:28:10.290 --> 00:28:10.910
But no, I check.

00:28:10.910 --> 00:28:12.970
I don't check them
obsessively.

00:28:17.398 --> 00:28:20.510
Yeah, what are you pointing
out, Brady?

00:28:20.510 --> 00:28:23.870
BRADY HARAN: There is someone
commenting, using your face

00:28:23.870 --> 00:28:25.680
and the name James
Grime on YouTube.

00:28:25.680 --> 00:28:27.550
And we should point out,
that is not James.

00:28:27.550 --> 00:28:28.900
That is just some--

00:28:28.900 --> 00:28:30.940
well, I won't use unsuitable
words.

00:28:30.940 --> 00:28:31.750
But that's someone who is--

00:28:31.750 --> 00:28:32.610
JAMES GRIME: It's not me.

00:28:32.610 --> 00:28:33.500
BRADY HARAN: --who is
being creative.

00:28:33.500 --> 00:28:34.540
And that's not James.

00:28:34.540 --> 00:28:38.307
And I personally don't think
people should be doing that.

00:28:38.307 --> 00:28:38.990
But who am I?

00:28:38.990 --> 00:28:41.020
I'm just some guy,
so there you go.

00:28:41.020 --> 00:28:43.720
Someone asked a question a bit
earlier that I did like.

00:28:43.720 --> 00:28:48.430
And that is, when your life is
so much mathematics, do you

00:28:48.430 --> 00:28:52.260
find yourself just doing,
without even meaning to, like,

00:28:52.260 --> 00:28:56.090
counting the number of times you
chewed that sandwich, and

00:28:56.090 --> 00:28:59.380
looking at a shape or a house
and thinking about dimensions

00:28:59.380 --> 00:29:01.780
and equations?

00:29:01.780 --> 00:29:03.200
JAMES GRIME: No, not really.

00:29:03.200 --> 00:29:06.790
I mean, we talked about
those-- vampires and

00:29:06.790 --> 00:29:08.586
arithmomania and things like
that, and counting

00:29:08.586 --> 00:29:09.260
the number of steps.

00:29:09.260 --> 00:29:10.185
And that's a real condition.

00:29:10.185 --> 00:29:11.880
There are people who do that.

00:29:11.880 --> 00:29:16.580
I don't think mathematicians, as
a rule, have arithmomania.

00:29:16.580 --> 00:29:18.700
I certainly do not.

00:29:18.700 --> 00:29:21.720
But maybe you're asking, maybe
in broader terms, do I look at

00:29:21.720 --> 00:29:24.320
the world and see
it as equations

00:29:24.320 --> 00:29:25.670
and things like that?

00:29:25.670 --> 00:29:30.260
And do you know, no,
I probably do not.

00:29:30.260 --> 00:29:31.960
BRADY HARAN: I mean, I'm not
going so much for the personal

00:29:31.960 --> 00:29:34.650
questions, because you know,
away from "Numberphile",

00:29:34.650 --> 00:29:37.910
you're your own man, but I do
have to ask, what pajamas do

00:29:37.910 --> 00:29:40.850
you wear to bed?

00:29:40.850 --> 00:29:42.300
JAMES GRIME: OK.

00:29:42.300 --> 00:29:43.910
BRADY HARAN: Just because I
didn't expect that question.

00:29:43.910 --> 00:29:46.610
Most of the questions
I can expect, but--

00:29:46.610 --> 00:29:47.390
JAMES GRIME: Oh, right.

